  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Plot is the causal sequence of events in a narrative — not merely what happens, but why one event leads to another. E.M. Forster made the classic distinction: \u0026ldquo;\u0026lsquo;The king died and then the queen died\u0026rsquo; is a story. \u0026lsquo;The king died, and then the queen died of grief\u0026rsquo; is a plot\u0026rdquo; [@forster1927]. Plot introduces causality, and causality creates meaning.\nAristotle established the foundational framework: a plot has a beginning, middle, and end, and its events should follow from each other by necessity or probability rather than mere sequence [@aristotle_poetics]. A plot whose events could be rearranged without consequence has no causal structure — it is episodic in the worst sense.\n",
